# Contracts and decisions discipline

Schemas (`schemas/`):

- Schemas define the trust boundary (master doc §6.3). Changing a schema's shape, enums,
  or required fields needs an ADR first (§12.5) — extending examples does not.
- Dialect is JSON Schema 2020-12; one schema resource per file; `$id` values are
  placeholder URIs until the irrevon.dev domain purchase closes (ADR-0023; see
  schemas/README.md).
- Every schema keeps both example suites honest: `valid-*.json` must pass, `invalid-*.json`
  must fail. If a change flips an example's status, that is a shape change — ADR first.
- Never add fields sourced from a proposed-but-unratified amendment as if settled; mark
  them with a `$comment` naming the amendment.

ADRs (`docs/decisions/`):

- Follow the template and numbering in `docs/decisions/README.md`. Take the next free id;
  never reuse one (`make integrity` enforces uniqueness).
- Accepted ADRs are append-only: to change a decision, write a new ADR that supersedes it
  and update only the old ADR's status line and the index.
- Filling in an OPEN ADR's decision and flipping its status to accepted is the one
  sanctioned in-place edit — and it is human-only. Agents propose text; humans ratify.
- Every ADR needs a concrete, observable reopen trigger.
